refactor.content:
The most important refactoring based on the review findings is to properly handle errors when reading the file. This not only improves the robustness of the code but also provides better feedback to the user in case something goes wrong.

**Improved Code Snippet:**

```go
func readFile(path string) (string, error) {
    data, err := ioutil.ReadFile(path)
    if err != nil {
        return "", err // Properly handle the error returned by ioutil.ReadFile
    }
    return string(data), nil
}

func main() {
    if len(os.Args) < 2 {
        fmt.Println("Usage: prog <file>") // Print usage message if no file is provided
        return
    }
    content, err := readFile(os.Args[1]) // Handle errors from readFile
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error reading file: %v\n", err) // Print error message if an error occurs
        return
    }
    fmt.Println(content)
}
```

**Comments on Changes:**
- **Line:** `func readFile(path string) string` -> Changed to `func readFile(path string) (string, error)` to handle potential errors.
- **Line:** `content := readFile(os.Args[1])` -> Changed to `content, err := readFile(os.Args[1])` and added error handling.

These changes ensure that the program is more reliable and provides meaningful feedback to the user.

